    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Description\n\n## Description\n\nHi, I wanted to change the way lsp detects **root_dir** in my projects. I tried these settings and none of them worked:\n``` lua\nreturn {\n  root_markers = { \".Rprofile\", \".git\" },\n  settings = { ... }\n}\n```\n``` lua\nreturn {\n  root_dir = function(bufnr, on_dir)\n    on_dir(vim.fs.root(bufnr, { \".Rprofile\", \".git\"}) or vim.uv.os_homedir())\n  end,\n  settings = { ... }\n}\n```\nIn all cases, it only detects projects that have `.git` started. For example, if my project only uses `.Rprofile` (without git) the root_dir detects my home directory.\n\n```\n/home/\n  R-project1/\n    .Rprofile\n    process.R\n  R-project2/\n    .git\n   process.R    \n```\nIn this example. `R-project1` root_dir is `/home/` and in the case of `R-project2`, root_dir is `/home/R-project2/`. I don't know if this is a problem with the plugin or is it from the r_language_server. I use the default plugin settings but make my own modifications in `lsp/r_language_server.lua`.\n\n## Expected Behavior\n\nCorrectly apply root_dir or root_markers configuration\n\n## Environment\n\n- nvim: 0.12.2\n- nvim-lspconfig: latest\n- R languageserver: 0.3.17\n- OS: Linux\n\n\n\n\n\n",
